Instituting a R350 basic income grant would inevitably lead to higher taxes and would mean taking some unpopular decisions according to Finance Minister Enoch Godongwana in his maiden budget speech on Wednesday. eNCA's Lindsay Dentlinger has more on this story. Courtesy of #DStv403 CAPE TOWN - The introduction of a permanent basic income grant could drive up taxes and increase the country’s debt. That’s the warning from Finance Minister Enoch Godongwana, who fielded questions from MPs on his maiden budget. WATCH | Reactions to Finance Minister's budget speech The extension of the R350 social relief of distress grant for another year will cost R44-billion. But just how sustainable it will be in the long term is still under consideration by Treasury. * eNCA's Lindsay Dentlinger reports.